<p><i><b>Miranda v. Arizona</b></i> consolidated with <i><b>Westover v. United States</b>,</i> <i><b>Vignera v. New York</b>,</i> and <i><b>California v. Stewart</b></i>), <span class="plainlinks">384 <a href="/wiki/United_States_Reports" title="United States Reports">U.S.</a> <a href="http://supreme.justia.com/us/384/436/case.html" class="external text" title="http://supreme.justia.com/us/384/436/case.html" rel="nofollow">436</a> (1966)</span>, was a <a href="/wiki/Landmark_decision" title="Landmark decision" class="mw-redirect">landmark</a> 5-4 decision of the <a href="/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States" title="Supreme Court of the United States">United States Supreme Court</a> which was argued February 28–March 1, 1966 and decided June 13, 1966. The <a href="/wiki/Court" title="Court">Court</a> held that both inculpatory and exculpatory statements made in response to <a href="/wiki/Interrogation" title="Interrogation">interrogation</a> by a <a href="/wiki/Defendant" title="Defendant">defendant</a> in <a href="/wiki/Police" title="Police">police</a> custody will be admissible at <a href="/wiki/Trial" title="Trial" class="mw-redirect">trial</a> only if the <a href="/wiki/Prosecution" title="Prosecution" class="mw-redirect">prosecution</a> can show that the defendant was informed of the right to consult with an <a href="/wiki/Lawyer" title="Lawyer">attorney</a> before and during questioning and of the right against self-incrimination prior to questioning by police, and that the defendant not only understood these rights, but voluntarily waived them.</p>
